Hiranya Gowda ** Dr. C.K. Hiranya Gowda, MD, FACS April 10, 1934 - December 22, 2021 **Dr. C.K. Hiranya Gowda **was an Indian-American ENT surgeon, professor of ENT surgery, philanthropist, mentor, entrepreneur, community leader, yoga teacher,** **past President of** India Association Of Nashville (IAN) in 1971-1972** and one of the founders of the** Sri Ganesha Temple **of Nashville. From his humble beginnings in Chamareddihalli, a village in Karnataka, he graduated from Mysore Medical College and immigrated to the USA in 1963 to further his medical training and career as an ENT surgeon. After moving to Nashville in 1970, he served as Professor and Chief of ENT at Nashville’s historical Meharry Medical College and Nashville General Hospital from 1972 to 1999. During that time, he began a private practice at Summit Medical Center (formerly known as Donelson Hospital) and retired in 2007. Throughout his time as a practicing physician, he continued to share his expertise in Mysore and Bangalore by remaining actively involved in many of the international ENT conferences and delivering CME lectures. Apart from his innumerable contributions to charitable causes in Nashville and other parts of the USA, he played a pivotal role in conceiving the Sri Ganesha Temple and bringing it to fruition as one of the founders and chief donors in the 1980s. Dr. Gowda generously donated his time and resources over the decades to Indian American organizations such as AAPI, Indian Association of Nashville (IAN), Nashville Kannada Koota, KSMD, AKKA, Tennessee Andhra Samithi, Hindu Temple Society of America, Ekal Vidyalaya, and the Hindu Monastery of Kaui. He was deeply committed to numerous charitable activities in India such as building a water tank for his village, funding the construction of schools, renovating ancient temples, establishing scholarships and a computer lab for rural students, providing meals for the needy, and promoting yoga and healthy living through his authorship of “GYM3”-a guide for yoga and healthy practices. In his free time, Dr. Gowda was an avid gardener, investor and grandfather. He lived a busy and productive life and he will be missed by all. He is survived by his wife of 60 years, Saraswathi Gowda, and their daughter and family (Kalpana, Chandrashekar, Chetan, Anand, Maithreya). The funeral service will be private for the family. Please send condolence notes to Kalpana's email: Kalpchand65@gmail.com or to Sarswati Gowda at 2025 Priest Road, Nashville, TN. 37215. \"*It is a privilege to serve mankind, for this is the worship of God. God is here, in all these human souls. He is the soul of man*\" –Swami Vivekananda “*The best way to find yourself is to lose yourself in the service of others*.” ― Mahatma Gandhi Our condolences and prayers. - 20:06:28","type":"photo","description":"Traditionally, the Chickasaw people used a hashtolaꞌ chokkaꞌ or winter house for warmth and insulation, and featured a central fire hearth. The poles used in its construction were heavier, and the exterior was covered in daub, which is a mixture of wet clay and grass. The walls were whitewashed with a mixture of white clay, water and crushed shells. \n\nUnlike the summer house with its sharp angles and rectangular shape, the winter house was more circular, and its plan resembled that of a snail shell, with a wraparound corridor entrance. This kept freezing cold wind and rain out and its narrow entrance could be easily defended against enemy intrusion. The winter house was topped off with a domed or conical roof supported in the center by four large posts supporting the rafters. Before the clay covering was dry, the roof was covered with shingles made of the tree bark or grass thatch laid down in circular courses starting at the bottom and ending at the top. \n\nReplicas of winter houses can be seen today at the Chickasaw Cultural Center located in Sulphur, 03:26:49","pageCategory":"CAUSE","verified":false},"languageCode":"und","legacyId":0,"id":"18335065|6752691138106738"},{"platformId":"503055433070371_6749918798383972","platform":"Facebook","date":"2021-12-29 07:58:03","updated":"2022-01-06 20:06:28","type":"photo","description":"The War Bonnet Facts-\n\nThe authentic and traditional feather War Bonnet was favored by the chiefs, war leaders and warriors of many tribes who inhabited the Great Plains including the Cheyenne, Sioux, Assiniboine and Chippewa. Every one of the feathers in the war bonnet headdress was a symbolic reflection of the brave deeds and battles that the warrior had been engaged in. The war bonnet was a symbol of high respect and a visible display of a warrior's bravery, honor and standing in his tribe.\nWar Bonnet Fact 1: The warriors of Native American Indian tribes wore a variety of different styles of war bonnets. These symbolic headdresses included Buffalo Horn Headdresses, Halo Warbonnets, Straight-up Feathered War bonnets, the crown and plume warbonnets and the famous long trailing feathered war bonnet.\nWar Bonnet Fact 2: The famous long, trailing feather war bonnets were worn by tribes such as the the Sioux and the Cheyenne.\nWar Bonnet Fact 3: The Buffalo Horn war bonnets, was worn by the Sioux and the Chippewa (Ojibwa) tribes, consisted of a buffalo hide skullcap with either long or short tails, with feathers attached, hanging from the back. The horns were polished and sometimes painted with symbolic colors and symbols. Only the bravest of warriors were given permission to wear the horned warbonnets.\nWar Bonnet Fact 4: The 'Straight-up' Feathered War bonnet which was taller and narrower than other headdresses with the feathers going straight up and worn by the Kiowa, Blackfoot and the Comanche tribes.\nWar Bonnet Fact 5: The Halo war bonnet had feathers fanning out to the back.\nWar Bonnet Fact 6: Feather crown and plume war bonnet was worn by tribes in California such as the Shasta and Chumash.\nWar Bonnet Fact 7: A Native Indian warrior earned a feather for each courageous act he accomplished.\nWar Bonnet Fact 8: The chief of every tribe had a special war bonnet. The feathers on the Chief's headdress were given to him due to the contributions he had made to the tribal community and a mark of great honor. The chief’s headdress consisted of many many feathers, each feather representing a good deed, which is why the long trailing warbonnets were often worn and associated with the Chief of a tribe.\nWar Bonnet Fact 9: Every feather in war bonnet headdress was awarded by the tribal elders for some great deed, usually in warfare. This practice lead to the expression \"a feather in his cap\".\nWar Bonnet Fact 10: The feathers were decorated in different styles, colors and designs that would signify why the feather was awarded to the person.\nWar Bonnet Fact 11: Each time a warrior earned a feather, he would either wear it or displayed it on a pole used for ceremonial occasions and rituals. Once a warrior had collected enough feathers, they were then made into a headdress.\nWar Bonnet Fact 12: Only the men of the tribe, usually the closest friends of the warrior, were involved in making the war bonnet headdress.\nWar Bonnet Fact 13: The most prized of all feathers was the Golden Eagle feather. The eagle was considered a messenger from the Great Spirit.\nWar Bonnet Fact 14: It is believed that the idea of wearing a war bonnet originated with the Sioux people.\nWar Bonnet Fact 15: There were different ways of earning the privilege and honor of being able to wear a war bonnet. A warrior who was the first to touch a fallen enemy in a battle could earn the privilege as this signified that the warrior was at the forefront of the fighting.\nWar Bonnet Fact 16: Meaning of bird feathers: Eagle feathers indicated great strength and courage, Crow feathers indicated skill and cunning, Falcon feathers represented speed, Hawk feathers indicated strength and vision, Hummingbird feathers represented intelligence, Owl feathers (wisdom) and Raven feathers (knowledge).","expandedLinks":[{"original":"https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=4463083953802194&set=gm.2994565524117310&type=3","expanded":"https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=4463083953802194&set=gm.2994565524117310&type=3"}],"link":"https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=4463083953802194&set=gm.2994565524117310&type=3","postUrl":"https://www.facebook.com/503055433070371/posts/6749918798383972","subscriberCount":0,"score":2.526315789473684,"media":[{"type":"photo","url":"https://scontent-sea1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/p600x600/270129256_4463083940468862_5271239719030967725_n.jpg?_nc_cat=102&ccb=1-5&_nc_sid=ca434c&_nc_ohc=kuF2rd3qL9wAX8W5sc9&_nc_ht=scontent-sea1-1.xx&oh=00_AT-2W4HTyJa3_rIWT5Waf9niRLM-n4EkXQBX7Ope_oPpNg&oe=61DE2DBA","height":720,"width":600,"full":"https://scontent-sea1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/p600x600/270129256_4463083940468862_5271239719030967725_n.jpg?_nc_cat=102&ccb=1-5&_nc_sid=ca434c&_nc_ohc=kuF2rd3qL9wAX8W5sc9&_nc_ht=scontent-sea1-1.xx&oh=00_AT-2W4HTyJa3_rIWT5Waf9niRLM-n4EkXQBX7Ope_oPpNg&oe=61DE2DBA"}],"statistics":{"actual":{"likeCount":22,"shareCount":17,"commentCount":1,"loveCount":8,"wowCount":0,"hahaCount":0,"sadCount":0,"angryCount":0,"thankfulCount":0,"careCount":1},"expected":{"likeCount":6,"shareCount":3,"commentCount":2,"loveCount":2,"wowCount":1,"hahaCount":0,"sadCount":0,"angryCount":0,"thankfulCount":0,"careCount":1}},"account":{"id":18335065,"name":"American Today is a day of mourning of our 38+2 Dakota Grandfathers, who were executed by hanging the day after Christmas, December 26, 1862, Mankato, Minnesota, 157 years ago.  \n\nOur Dakota ancestors lived a good life in Minnesota (Mni Sota) for centuries.  Then when the settlers moved west the land was taken from them.  This led to conflict and all the same soldiers who fought our ancestors, were appointed to the military commission, who were biased and sentenced 303 of our ancestors to death.  Our ancestors didn’t understand English nor did they have legal counsel representing them, they had no idea what crimes they were being tried in court for.  This was completely lopsided and led to one-sided accounts and the hatred led to continuous pressure on President Lincoln to punish our ancestors\n\nPresident Abraham Lincoln eventually lowered the execution down to 38.  The Dakota 38+2 execution was the largest mass execution in our country’s history.  Throughout America, around 99 million out of 100 million of our ancestors died during westward expansion.  \n\nPray for our ancestors, live for our ancestors, heal for our ancestors.  Educate others about this history, so we will never repeat it and we hope our children will all disable racism and create a better future.  We do better, when we know better.\n\n~Always Remember the Dakota 38+2, and blessings to the horse back riders, runners and those who walk for awareness in Remembrance every year.  Hecetuwedo, Mitakuye
